  "text": "Apache Flink's windowing API provides a clear extension mechanism for custom window assigners through the following architectural components:\n\n## WindowAssigner (Abstract Base Class)\nFile: `flink-runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/flink/streaming/api/windowing/assigners/WindowAssigner.java`\n\nDevelopers implementing custom window assigners must extend `WindowAssigner<T, W extends Window>` and implement four abstract methods:\n1. `Collection<W> assignWindows(T element, long timestamp, WindowAssignerContext context)` - Assigns zero or more windows to an incoming element based on its timestamp\n2. `Trigger<T, W> getDefaultTrigger()` - Returns the default trigger for this window assigner\n3. `TypeSerializer<W> getWindowSerializer(ExecutionConfig executionConfig)` - Provides a serializer for the window type\n4. `boolean isEventTime()` - Indicates whether windows are based on event time or processing time\n\n## MergingWindowAssigner (Extension for Session-Style Windows)\nFile: `flink-runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/flink/streaming/api/windowing/assigners/MergingWindowAssigner.java`\n\nFor window assigners that support merging (particularly session windows), developers extend `MergingWindowAssigner<T, W extends Window>` which adds the critical extension point:\n- `void mergeWindows(Collection<W> windows, MergeCallback<W> callback)` - Determines which windows should be merged and invokes the callback to perform the merge\n\n## Trigger Lifecycle Methods\nFile: `flink-runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/flink/streaming/api/windowing/triggers/Trigger.java`\n\nThe `Trigger<T, W extends Window>` abstract class defines four lifecycle methods that custom triggers implement:\n1. `TriggerResult onElement(T element, long timestamp, W window, TriggerContext ctx)` - Called when an element arrives at a pane\n2. `TriggerResult onProcessingTime(long time, W window, TriggerContext ctx)` - Called when a processing-time timer fires\n3. `TriggerResult onEventTime(long time, W window, TriggerContext ctx)` - Called when an event-time timer fires\n4. `void onMerge(W window, OnMergeContext ctx)` - Called when windows are merged (requires `canMerge()` to return true)\n\nAdditional methods:\n- `boolean canMerge()` - Default returns false; override and return true if the trigger supports merging\n- `void clear(W window, TriggerContext ctx)` - Clears any state maintained by the trigger for a window\n\n## Reference Implementation: EventTimeSessionWindows\nFile: `flink-streaming-java/src/main/java/org/apache/flink/streaming/api/windowing/assigners/EventTimeSessionWindows.java`\n\nThis `MergingWindowAssigner<Object, TimeWindow>` implementation demonstrates the pattern:\n- `assignWindows()` creates a single `TimeWindow(timestamp, timestamp + sessionTimeout)` for each element\n- `mergeWindows()` delegates to the static utility `TimeWindow.mergeWindows(windows, c)` which handles overlapping window merging\n- `getDefaultTrigger()` returns `EventTimeTrigger.create()`\n- `isEventTime()` returns true\n- `getWindowSerializer()` returns `new TimeWindow.Serializer()`\n\n## TimeWindow Output Type\nFile: `flink-runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/flink/streaming/api/windowing/windows/TimeWindow.java`\n\nThe concrete `TimeWindow` class represents time intervals:\n- Constructor: `TimeWindow(long start, long end)` where end is exclusive\n- Key accessors: `getStart()` and `getEnd()`\n- Utility methods: `intersects(TimeWindow other)` and `cover(TimeWindow other)` for merging logic\n- Static utility: `mergeWindows(Collection<TimeWindow> windows, MergeCallback<TimeWindow> c)` implements the overlapping window merge algorithm used by session assigners\n\nThis architecture enables developers to create custom window assigners by implementing the `assignWindows()` method, and optionally extend `MergingWindowAssigner` and implement `mergeWindows()` for session-style semantics."
}

